About this hotel

Set among restaurants and museums, this polished riad is a 7-minute walk from the 12th-century Koutoubia Mosque and 5 km from Marrakesh Menara Airport.

Check-in time: 2:00 PM
Check-out time: 12:00 PM

    Stayed there for a few days with two other friends. Our room was so spacious and so cozy! The staff were AMAZING and incredibly hospitable, literally took care of all our needs. One of my friends needed to go out to the Medina for a tour …
    Stayed there for a few days with two other friends. Our room was so spacious and so cozy! The staff were AMAZING and incredibly hospitable, literally took care of all our needs. One of my friends needed to go out to the Medina for a tour and the riad owner even drove her out on his motorcycle. Even if you decided to stay in for the day, there were many places to hang out (room, pool area, terrace) and they had a pretty wide variety of food as well. The riad was located within some alleys that took getting used to, but at night, there is a security guard at the entrance of the alleys and he walked us all the way back to our riad. I don’t think I’d return to Marrakech again, but I’m glad we stayed here because it made for such a peaceful home for the few days!

    Rebecca Yamina3 years ago on Google
    5/5
    This was by far the best riad we stayed in. The interior design was so classy. It has a pool which was very inviting after a hot day haggling in the souks. The room was really large and the bed was so comfortable. The breakfast was big and …
    This was by far the best riad we stayed in. The interior design was so classy. It has a pool which was very inviting after a hot day haggling in the souks. The room was really large and the bed was so comfortable. The breakfast was big and delicious and they also have an extensive menu with Moroccan and Western cuisines for lunch and dinner and sandwiches and burgers 24/7. Above all, the staff were so friendly, always wanting a chat. They also provide lots of excursions and activities at really reasonable prices. We went on a day trip to the Ouzoud Falls and we had a cooking class with their chef.
    The only thing which was slightly difficult about our stay at Riad Farhan was trying to find it. Our Google maps thought it was in a different place. We needed to call the riad to pick us up because we were so lost. The riad is down a series of alleys that aren't on Google maps, so it would be best to call them up beforehand. However, at night there is a security guard that will escort you through the alley ways. That was a nice touch.

    Michael Durlacher4 years ago on Google
    5/5
    Nice and cosy Riad operated by friendly staff. Location within the Medina is quite nice for exploring the city centre. We had airport transfer organised by the Riad (15€ for one direction) and were picked up by a staff member at the drop …
    Nice and cosy Riad operated by friendly staff. Location within the Medina is quite nice for exploring the city centre. We had airport transfer organised by the Riad (15€ for one direction) and were picked up by a staff member at the drop off point. It may be a little hard to find on ones own.
    The rooms are clean and spacious enough, the rooftop with its daybeds is a nice spot for a little break. Breakfast is good with tea, coffee, fresh orange juice and moroccan bread, but could offer a little more options (just sweet things like jam, yoghurt, but no savory options).
    If there is a negative point, it may be the fact that it can be quite noisy in the late evenings or the early mornings, as all the room doors are not holding off the noise from the patio. But this may be the same in other Riads, I suppose, as a result of the way they are built.

    Beni Gulyás4 years ago on Google
    5/5
    Clean and atmospheric riad. Very nice and communicative staff. Room was big, authentic and cleaned every day. The bed was huge and comfy. Our room had an air conditioner which we used to heat our room at night. The staff helped us with a …
    Clean and atmospheric riad. Very nice and communicative staff. Room was big, authentic and cleaned every day. The bed was huge and comfy. Our room had an air conditioner which we used to heat our room at night. The staff helped us with a map and gave us tips on how to get around in Marrakesh. Breakfast is a must. The dishes are mostly traditional dishes, but if you don't like it there are types of spagetties too. Only downside was to get there, a little complicated but after first time you get used to it: we got dropped off by taxi at the king's residence near the riad. Go East on the road and when you see a red security booth turn left, go ahead until dead end and turn left and so on. The rule is simple: left - dead end - left - dead end - left - etc. until you get to the final end of the road where is the riad's entrance.

    Medina

    Hammam bath houses and covered spice and textile souks line the maze of cobblestoned lanes in the Medina, which occupies Marrakesh’s original fortified citadel. At night, Jemaa el-Fna square teems with snake charmers, folk dancers, and street food vendors serving all manner of food. Bahia Palace and Le Jardin Secret are 19th-century complexes open to the public, with ornate courtyards, mosaics, and gardens.

    About this hotel

    Set among restaurants and museums, this polished riad is a 7-minute walk from the 12th-century Koutoubia Mosque and 5 km from Marrakesh Menara Airport. …

    The 5 warmly decorated rooms feature free Wi-Fi and en suite bathrooms; some have sitting areas and/or sleep up to 3 people.

    A courtyard features an outdoor pool. There’s a peaceful lounge and a rooftop terrace. Breakfast is available.
